{"/service/ndnp/ak/batch_ak_chinooksalmon_ver03/data/sn84020662/00414185940/1949030901/1020.xml":{"full_text":"THE NOME NUGGET\nPublished Monday, Wednesday and Friday by the\nNOME PUBLISHING CO.\nNOME, ALASKA\nTelephone: Main 125 P. O. Box 610\n$1.50 PER MONTH $16.00 A YEAR\nW. A. Boucher .Owner-Publisher\nEmily Boucher .Local Editor\nEntered as second class matter October 14. 1943, at the postoffice\nat Nome, Alaska, under the Act of March 3, 1879.\nNome, Alaska, Wednesday, March 9, 1949\nNEW TAXES, NEW APPROPRIATIONS KEEP PACE\nI\n(By James Hutcheson)\nJUNEAU, (/P)\u2014As the legislature heads into the\nhome stretch, the Senate finance committee chairman1\nestimates that new taxes are just about keeping pace-1\nwith the budget and new appropriations.\nSen. John Butrovich, Jr., Fairbanks Republican,\nwho keeps an eagle eye on the probable income and out\ngo in his key chairmanship, lists $18,000,000 as the\nprobable \u201ctake\u201d for the general fund from taxes now\non the books. They include the new income and general\nproperty taxes and the quadrupled fish trap taxes.\n(Some legislators have expressed fear the fish trap tax\nmay be open to court challenge as possibly discrimina\ntory because of the sharp increase).\nButrovich bases his figures on the estimates of the tax\ncommissioner, with a bit of paring on figures he con\nsidered too optimistic.\nHe lists another $5,047,000 as the revenue potential\nfor tax bills which were in his committee\u2019s hands March\n2. (They did not include either the major general busi\nness license tax or the $370,000 addition to the school\ntax, both of which have passed the House).\nThe bills before the committee with the estimated\n$5,047,000 potential are the raw fish-canned salmon tax,\ntobacco tax and admissions tax measures. All are given\na good chance of legislative approval.\nThat would make the estimated revenue total rough\nyl $23,000,000, without figuring the business license\nlevy.\nA $20,000,000 revenue estimate was made by Sen.\nHoward Lvng, Democratic rules committee chairman,\nin a floor discussion of finances a few days ago. He es\ntimated there might possibly be a surplus for the bien\nnium.\nAgainst the revenue prospect, there is the $17,403,341\nrequest by the board of budget. On top of that, Butro\nvich lists $434,000 additional specific appropriations\nwhich the legislature has made and the governor has\nsigned. The major items are $250,000 for the Alaska\nHousing Authoritv, $50,000 for legislative session\nexpenses, $50,000 increased aid to dependent children\nand $50,000 for increased hair seal bounties. In addi\ntion, there is a $195,000 total of continuing appropria\ntions from the 1947 session\u2014$20,000 for a Territoria1\naudit, $165,000 for hospital construction and $10,000\nfor the game commission\u2014for which money is supposed\nto be provided when it is available.\nThose items raise the total of budget requests and en\nacted appropriations to $18,032,577.\nThat barely over-balances the $18,000,000 revenue\nestimate from taxes now in effect.\nButrovich pointed out that the budget figures might\nbe cut some. Most departments included salary in\ncreases which they might not get.\nBut while most of the tax proposals have reached the\nfinance committee, the parade of bills with new appro\npriation proposals\u2014large or small\u2014continues.\nBills before the finance committee with appropria\ntions, at the date of the chairman\u2019s summary, were:\n$250,000 for setting up a department of fisheries; $93,\n535 for raising Territorial salaries; $900 for a labor de\npartment deficiency.\nThe finance chairman\u2019s revenue estimates for the\ngeneral fund are:\nAnticipated prior to legislative sessions$5,000,000\nNew income tax law. 4,000,000\nAdditional fish trap tax. 4,000,000\nGeneral property tax. 5,000,000\nTOTAL..$18,000,000\nEstimates of revenue potential of bills before commit\nIT* A SMALL WORLD\n_\ntee:\nRaw fish-canned salmon tax as amended\nby Senate taxation committee .$3,871,500\nTaxation committee sub for one section\nof it 160,700\nTobacco taxes 827,400\nAdmissions tax (only one on list not ap\nproved by House) 187,500\nI\nTOTAL. $5,047,100\n*_\nEMPLOYMENT AND 1949\n(Cincinnati Enquirer)\nWhile there has been some recession in employment,\nmany authorities say the situation is not yet indicative\nof an important decline in the number of Americans\ngainfully employed. That a leveling-off is in process,\nhowever, seems indisputable.\nIndustrial organizations, with tremendous backlogs\nof orders, were in the labor market tooth and nail for\nseveral years immediately after the war. During those\nyears the shortage of labor was acute. Management felt\nforced to take all the men it could get, regardless of\nabilities, training\u2014and often regardless of price. This\nsituation resulted in inefficiencies\u2014inefficiencies re\nsulted both in price and quality; or product.\nAs the employment picture returns to balance, these\ndetracting factors will shrink. Employees will be as\nsured of jobs, but the day of pay without production\nwill pass. This will react to the great benefit of the con\nsumer\u2014as well as to the ultimate benefit of labor and\nmanagement. Cutthroat competition for workers also\nis on the wane\u2014and that too will have a beneficial ef\nfect on our entire industrial structure.\nIn general, the outlook is encouraging\u2014encouragin'?|\nfor management.'We can hope that industry, within the'\ncoming months, will arrive at a state of balance in\nwhich nrices, supply, employment and profits will as\nsume the more normal levels which go with true and\nsatisfactory prosperity.\nBAKU RESTORATION PUSHED\nMOSCOW, (/P)\u2014From Baku it is reported that the\nlast three years have seen progress in the restoration of\noil output of the important oil fields of this petroleum\ncenter. An editorial in \u201cBaku Worker\u201d stated recently\nthat during the first three years of the postwar five year\nplan, 1946, 1947, 1948, oil production there had increas\ned 21.9 percent. In addition it stated oil refining had in\ncreased by 31.4 percent in the same period and that nat\nural gas extraction had increased 23.6 percent.\nThe Chairman of the State Planning Commission of\nthe USSR, N. A.^Voznessensky, announced in 1946 in\nconnection with the postwar fourth Five Year Plan that\nduring this plan Baku oil output would increase by 50\npercent and reach 17,000,000 metric tons in 1950.\nWe can\u2019t expect to get on with people by telling them\noff!\nWASHINGTON\nNEWS LETTER\n(By Mary Lee Council) I\n\nFour of Delegate Bartlett\u2019s bills,\nhaving been reported favorably\nby the House Public Lands Com\nmittee, will come up for vote in\nthe House within the next few\nweeks. In addition three private\nrelief bills sponsored by the Dele\ngate have been reported favorably\ni by the House judiciary committee,\nand one such measure was passed\nby the lower house last week.\nOne of the four genlral pieces\nof legislation would provide that\npatented mining claims in Alaska,\nfor purposes of taxation by the\nTerritorial legislature, would be\nvalued at a flat rate fixed by the\nlegislature or at the price paid the\nUnited States.\nThe Alaska Council of Boy\nScouts would be able to buy\nthrough the secretary of the inte- L\nrior 240 acres of land situated\nmidway between Anchorage and\nPalmer on the Anchorage-Palmer\nhighway if the second measure re\nported is enacted into law. The\nland is desired for recreational\nand other public purposes.\nAlaska will have a princess in\nthe Cherry Festival scheduled for\n|Washing:on the latter part of\nMarch or early in April, depend-\neat upon the blooming period of\nI the blossoms.\nDelegate Bartlett has designated\nMiss Virginia daGanahl to repre\nsent the Territory. Miss deGanahl,.\nof Juneau, is the daughter of Mrs.\ndeGanahl ami the late Command\ner Joe deGanahl, USN. She is at\ntending Mount Vernon Seminary\nfor Girls in Virginia.\nDelegate Bartlett, pointing out\nthat the plan under which the\nagreement with Alaska Steamship\nCompany was recently approved.\ni like previous plans have been\ntemporary only, and has asked\nCongress to appropriate $50,000\nto work out a long-range program\nto solve the Alaska shipping prob\nlem. He has proposed that the In\nterior Department Appropriation\nBill for the fiscal year 1950, now\ni being considered on the House t\nside, include such a sum, as he be-\nlieves that officials of that depart\ni ment are the best equipped in the\nfederal government by their\nknowledge of the situation to work\nout the long-desired solution to\nthe problem.\nGrant R. Jackson, president of\nthe Miners and Merchants Bank\nof Alaska, is a Washington visitor\nfrom Nome.\nj Excise-Tax Cut\nMade G. O. P.\u2019s\nMajor Goal\nI WASHINGTON, <tV) The\nHouse Republican leadership to\nday made a cut in wartime excise\ntaxes its major objective for this\nCongress.\nAt its first meeting of the year,\nthe party\u2019s House policy commit\ntee approved a statement saying\n\u201cthe wartime excise taxes should\nbe cut back at once to the prewar\n1941 rates.\u201d\nExcise taxes are the levies on\ntelephone bills, railroad tickets,\nfurs, luggage and the like. All of\nthem were raised sharply during\nthe war.\nThe G. O. P. committee took no\nstand on the question of general\ntax increases or reductions. Presi\ndent Truman is asking for a four\nbillion dollar increase in taxes on^\ncorporations and persons in higher\nincome brackets.","height":"28048","width":"20368"}}
